The simplest approach I&#39;ve found is that if there is need for only one
instance of some class in a system, to just create only one instance of that
type.

Adding extra code just to stop me creating more than one is always, in my
experience, counter-productive.  It&#39;s more code to write, test and maintain
and it gets in the way when I do need to create more than one.  For example,
in unit tests.  Or when requirements change.

--Nat



On 30/07/07, jason r tibbetts &lt;tibbettj@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;   Pat,
&gt;
&gt; &gt; This may be a bit off charter, but I&#39;ve been reading some well argued
&gt; &gt; articles that have names such as &quot;Why is Singleton evil?&quot; and at the top
&gt; &gt; of the list are troubles that the singleton pattern causes for unit
&gt; &gt; testing. (which is on topic.)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The usual suggestions for rewriting the code are offered, such as using
&gt; &gt; a factory class to allocate/create objects, and always always just
&gt; &gt; returning the one and only.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; So far, so good. But, the Factory class has to keep a store of
&gt; &gt; anti-singletons. And the usual call is something like
&gt; &gt; AntiSingleton anAnti = Factory.createAntiSingleton();
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Which is used statically, and implies that the Factory is a singleton so
&gt; &gt; its cache of AntiSingletons can be kept in one and only one store.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I&#39;m not seeing how changing the Singleton class to a class that needs
&gt; &gt; the singleton Factory class has done anything. We&#39;ve still got a
&gt; &gt; singleton, and so all arguments that there is implied coupling, and bad
&gt; &gt; karma for testing still hold.
&gt;
&gt; I don&#39;t see any mention yet in this thread of the simplest solution of
&gt; them all: put all of the singleton&#39;s implementation in a non-singleton
&gt; abstract base class, then subclass it as a singleton. The abstract base
&gt; class can be subclassed separately for testing. In other words,
&gt;
&gt; // abstract base class
&gt; public abstract class Foo {
&gt; protected Foo() { }
&gt;
&gt; public String getBar() { return &quot;bar!&quot;; }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; // singleton implementation
&gt; public final class TheOneTrueFoo extends Foo {
&gt; private TheOneTrueFoo() { super(); }
&gt;
&gt; public static Foo getInstance() { return foo; }
&gt;
&gt; private final static Foo = new TheOneTrueFoo();
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; // test-only implementation
&gt; public final class TestFoo {
&gt; public TestFoo() { super(); }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Voila! The 3 statements in the singleton implementation go untested, but
&gt; all of the rest of Foo can be tested normally.
&gt;
